snippet.textDisplay: I once read somewhere that the English have kept a love of Robin Hood thanks in part to pre-Norman conquest view of outlaws. They were usually outlawed for a period of time for a petty crime or something that got them banished for a bit, but with the assumption that they could come home afterwards (usually). Also, with all the political shenanigans of conquest, trade, re-conquered, Vikings, etc., putting a giant middle finger to power was basically an English human right. Which translates pretty well for Americans. (Terry Cook's "Mideival Lives", I think was the book.)

snippet.textDisplay: Hi Overly Sarcastic Productions here's a new idea for your Legends Summarized: Why not do ''Ivanhoe'' it take place in 12th-century England with colorful descriptions of a tournament, outlaws, a witch trail and divisions between Jews and Christians. It also shows important influence on popular perceptions of Robin Hood, Richard the Lionheart, and King John(since you mentioned about him and Sir Walter Scott, plus this genre has historical novel and chivalric romance). Or how about "A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court" by Samuel Langhorne Clemens AKA Mark Twain. It is a satire of feudalism and monarchy that also celebrates homespun ingenuity and democratic values while questioning the ideals of capitalism and outcomes of the Industrial Revolution(plus this genre has humor, satire, alternate history, science fiction AKA time travel, and fantasy too!)

The hilarious thing about Robin Hood's popularity is that, from the stories I've read, he really wasn't robbing in order to to give to the poor.

Sure, he had a big heart, and he would often go way out of his way to help total strangers, but he was robbing the rich for money (and also because he was a restless scoundrel). It's just that he was smart enough to spread enough of that wealth around that all of the locals "super couldn't find his hideout" and "totally hadn't seen him pass through just now."

Madlad.

I am disappointed though. Didn't even mention how Green Arrow is inspired by Robin Hood ore how the newest Robin Hood movie (with Jamie Fox and Taron Egerton) was great but heavily historically inaccurate (I mean, is it really that hard to design proper time appropriate costume? It just felt off the entire time).


I did recently have an argument with someone about a certain big youtuber who was robbed. It was about Pewdiepie. In that discussion, Robin Hood was brought up and Felix's wealth was mentioned by the person. I will say before I continue that I love the Robin Hood story. I've even based a character in a story I'm writing on him. But I do think that frankly, the original story may be outdated. I honestly don't know if Robin Hood had a code against robbing people who made their money fairly or anything but I think it needs to be clarified that robbing from people who have earned their money shouldn't be praised.


The convo came about after I shared the 'New Guy' meme and praised the New Guy character. The person messaged me defending the original artist of the meme and basically said that "rich people deserve to be robbed from for being rich/ having more money than others (her)." Obviously, this is an idiotic point of view. No one deserves to be robbed from just for having more of something. If it's karma though for their actions then, in cases, sure— but there's still the difference that Robin Hood (later versions) gave back to the poor.


I think the Robin Hood character should steal from those who deserve it. Criminals and people who use their riches to hurt others. Corrupt politicians and organizations. But he should also stop people who steal from others for selfish reasons or from people who have earned their money or don't have money. Maybe the original was more like this then I'm aware though.

snippet.textDisplay:
Fun facts:
1) Robin Hood or Robin Hode were very common nicknames for numerous criminals in Medieval England even before the legend was first written in the late Medieval, early Renaissance Ages suggesting the name was inspired by a now forgotten slang
2) Robin didn't steal from the rich but rather stole taxes from a tyrannical prince in the name of the much more loved king
3) hardly any modern adaptations are accurate to the tales

snippet.textDisplay:
My house is about 1 hour from a place called Robin Hood's Stride, which is a large rock formation with two huge pillars on each side. The legend around it says that while being chased by the Sheriff's men, Robin Hood climbed the rocks to the top and scaled a pillar to escape, but was then stuck. The Sheriff's men circled the pillar, sure that they had caught Robin Hood now, as the other pillar stood at a distance of more than 50 feet. However, quick and clever Robin Hood was able to jump the impossible distance, and had scrambled down the pillar and run away into the forest before the men could follow him.
If you look up a picture of the stride, you might recognise parts of it, as it was featured in a small film called The Princess Bride. It was also my favourite place to go climbing as a kid.

snippet.textDisplay:
) The National Civic Council (NCC), a think tank based in Melbourne, Australia, held its annual national conference from February 7-9, 2020. A Falun Gong practitioner was invited to speak on the first day of the conference. He detailed practitioners’ peaceful resistance against the 20-year-long persecution of Falun gong in China and crimes against humanity committed by the Chinese communist regime.


Representatives of the Falun Gong, Tibet, Uyghur and Hong Kong communities were invited to speak at the NCC’s 2020 national conference. A Falun Gong practitioner answers questions from the audience.

The main speaker that night was the Hon. Kevin Andrews, a member of the Australian House of Representatives. There were over 100 attendees, including NCC members from across Australia, representatives from other organizations, and the public. The topic discussed was “Why the government is considering a Magnitsky Act to support human rights in authoritarian states.” Falun Gong practitioners, China democracy groups, and representatives of the Hong Kong, Uyghur and Tibetan communities were invited to speak and participate in a Q&A session.

Kevin Andrews served as minister for various federal agencies over the course of 15 years. He is currently presiding over a public inquiry into the passing of the Magnitsky Act in Australia. The act aims to sanction and punish individuals and their family members for violating human rights or their involvement in the persecution of religious belief. At present, 28 countries have already passed or intend to pass laws similar to the U.S. Magnitsky Act.

The NCC is an Australian think tank founded in the 1940s with the objective of preserving traditional values such as the family and the integrity of human life. The organization has been publishing a current affairs magazine–the News Weekly–since 1943. The publication focuses on ethics and is distributed all over Australia. In recent years, the magazine has published several articles on forced organ harvesting from prisoners of conscience in China.

The act aims to sanction and punish individuals and their family members for violating human rights or their involvement in the persecution of religious belief. At present, 28 countries have already passed or intend to pass laws similar to the U.S. Magnitsky Act.

The NCC is an Australian think tank founded in the 1940s with the objective of preserving traditional values such as the family and the integrity of human life. The organization has been publishing a current affairs magazine–the News Weekly–since 1943. The publication focuses on ethics and is distributed all over Australia. In recent years, the magazine has published several articles on forced organ harvesting from prisoners of conscience in China.
